[Public education of rabies remains a need, even in developed
countries. The movie industry sensationalizes the furious form of
rabies. This is the form where there is vicious behavior and often
slobbering at the mouth. However, there is a dumb form of rabies
where animals are withdrawn, quiet, subdued. In some animals that are
naturally quite and withdrawn it may be difficult to recognize this
form.
Every public and private school should have film showing the
different forms of rabies and show them to students in every grade
level and enforce the importance of reporting animal bites,
especially from stray animals. It should also be stressed that owning
animals is a responsibility involving rabies shots and health checks.
Despite veterinarians preaching to their clients, there remain scores
of animal owners who do not take seriously the health consequences of
their animals or themselves, in just such a situation as this.
Unfortunately, as we become a less rural society and one that is more
urbanized, there is the tendency to believe that rabies cannot happen
in a city. In reality that is far from the truth. As we encroach on
the habitat of wildlife, they are left with adapting to our urban
ways. Consequently, our risk of exposure to rabies may be increased.
Let us hope such a lesson as this serves as a catalyst to inspire
these communities to host rabies vaccination clinics and to encourage
responsible pet ownership. - Mod.TG]
